        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1395531552" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7463065696127281255">Ugh why did I suffer through this book? <br/><br/>I typically love all things Arthurian but as soon as this book took off into the land of mind reading and telepathic links I couldn&apos;t roll my eyes harder. <br/><br/>Road to Avalon is a romantic historical fiction focusing on a pleasant love affair between King Arthur and Morgan (who we know as the evil Morgan le Fey). Of course, many of the character tropes that legend has attributed to the standard characters were lost in this retelling, with it being similar to th</span>
  <span id="freeText7463065696127281255" style="display:none">Ugh why did I suffer through this book? <br /><br />I typically love all things Arthurian but as soon as this book took off into the land of mind reading and telepathic links I couldn't roll my eyes harder. <br /><br />Road to Avalon is a romantic historical fiction focusing on a pleasant love affair between King Arthur and Morgan (who we know as the evil Morgan le Fey). Of course, many of the character tropes that legend has attributed to the standard characters were lost in this retelling, with it being similar to the King Arthur movie of the 2000s (see: Clive Owen and Kiera Knightly and Romans). Thus I found the latter half of the book incredibly boring. Honestly the back of the book's description was more exciting. <br /><br />Additionally the writing was poor and jumpy with various third person perspectives bogging down the text as they lacked fluidity, distinctions, and an exciting plot.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7463065696127281255" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
